{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1da74fbe-0ce7-4e4f-8865-599de5690b84","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use platform compiler directives (`#if ANDROID`, `#elif IOS`) to keep platform code separated.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnActivated`, etc.\n\nThis keeps all lifecycle wiring in one place without needing custom platform projects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"af5a3bda-7110-48ff-b569-348c8c6e261c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"E830:2827DA:2525D33:2934102:69F93F2A"},"id":"685f5257-7b8c-41c0-8288-d52a1f2328d5","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:52:01.379Z","parentId":"b3735e33-ef33-4776-919e-6eb868773fbe"}
